mands for accountability and with businesslike managerial systems that are endemic to the private sector. In this volume, a team of international experts shows that these influences are relative. They present theoretical and empirical insights on broader changes in and around professional work in healthcare, social welfare, education, and policing. They also analyze coping mechanisms of professionals, which vary from sector to sector and they argue that public professionals will need to develop new skills for working in reconfigured public services.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aCivil servicevCongresses. 0aProfessional employees. 0aSocial servicevCongresses. 4aPolitics and Government. 4aSOC. 4aSocial and Political Sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh1 aAckroyd, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBekkers, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGulikers, Huub, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoijtink, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHupe, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKwak, Arie-Jan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNewman, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoordegraaf, Mirko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNoordegraaf, Mirko, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSmullen, Amanda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteijn, Bram, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSteijn, Bram, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTonkens, Evelien, econtributor.4ctb4https://i